  "aspect": "vertical", "theme": "navy", "fps": 30, "crossfade": 0.6,
  "voiceover": "So who made God? It feels like a knockout — if everything needs a maker, then God needs one too, and the whole idea collapses. But look at what's actually being claimed. The argument never says 'everything has a cause.' It says something narrower: whatever begins to exist has a cause. The universe began to exist, so it needs a cause beyond itself. God, by definition, never began — he is eternal. So he isn't an arbitrary exception; he simply falls outside a rule that was only ever about things that begin. Asking what made God is like asking what the bachelor's wife is doing tonight. The question assumes what's already been ruled out. Not a knockout. A category error.",
  "source": "answers/who-made-god.html",
